onInputStarted.name: onInputStarted
onInputStarted.comment: User has started a keyword input session by typing the extension's keyword. This is guaranteed to be sent exactly once per input session, and before any onInputChanged events.

onInputChanged.name: onInputChanged
onInputChanged.comment: User has changed what is typed into the omnibox.

onInputEntered.name: onInputEntered
onInputEntered.comment: User has accepted what is typed into the omnibox.

onInputCancelled.name: onInputCancelled
onInputCancelled.comment: User has ended the keyword input session without accepting the input.

available.name: available
available.comment:
Returns true if the API is available. The common causes of an API not being avilable are:

  • a permission is missing in the application's manifest.json file
  • the API is defined on a newer version of Chrome then the current runtime

sendSuggestions.name: sendSuggestions
sendSuggestions.comment:
A callback passed to the onInputChanged event used for sending suggestions back to the browser.

chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeOmnibox.sendSuggestions.suggestResults An array of suggest results

setDefaultSuggestion.name: setDefaultSuggestion
setDefaultSuggestion.comment:
Sets the description and styling for the default suggestion. The default suggestion is the text that is displayed in the first suggestion row underneath the URL bar.

chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeOmnibox.setDefaultSuggestion.suggestion A partial SuggestResult object, without the 'content' parameter.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeOmnibox.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

  • a permission is missing in the application's manifest.json file
  • the API is defined on a newer version of Chrome then the current runtime

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeOmnibox.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeOmnibox.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeOmnibox.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeOmnibox.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeOmnibox.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeOmnibox.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.
